Level 1: Improving Matching and Ranking

For this level, weâ€™re going to explore three common ways of improving matching ranking:

Handling language â€œodditiesâ€ through query matching and content analysis

Using query-independent factors like sales rank

Using query-dependent factors like query logs (Optional)

To set the stage, letâ€™s consider a few common scenarios that happen in search:

Scenario 1: Marketing Terms, Branded Products and other abuses of a language

Quick, whatâ€™s the proper spelling of Appleâ€™s flagship phone?Â  Is it: a) iphone, b) i phone, c) iPhone, or d) i-phone?

Next question: which of the following queries should result in finding the car BMW C 300 4MATIC: a) BMW C300, b) BMW 4MATIC, c) BMW c 300 d) all of them.

For the first question, the answer is C, for the second, the answer is D.

In all cases, these are all likely (valid?) ways your users will query your search engine. Luckily, OpenSearch has tools to help us handle these types of scenarios, most notably in this case, the Word Delimiter Filter Graph as well as fuzzy query matching, both of which we will explore in this part of the project.Â  Additionally, in cases where OpenSearch canâ€™t handle them, we can build our own tokenizers, filters, and analyzers.Â  The latter is outside the scope of this class, but there are resources online to help you if need be.

Scenario 2: Query-Independent Factors AKA Popularity FTW!

Can you name your best-selling product?Â  What about your most popular document in your search engine or on your website?Â  If youâ€™ve been operating a search engine or a business for long enough to have some notion of the overall popularity or authoritativeness of any or all of items in your index, chances are such that, regardless of query, if you boosted the resulting documents by this known ranking value, your results are likely to be better.

Popularity, sales rank, page rank and other query-independent factors are often very strong signals for ranking.Â  This intuitively makes sense. When someone searches for iPhone, odds are they want either the top-selling phone itself or a top-selling accessory, and not just something that matches iPhone based on TF-IDF.Â  Since you explored much of this in week 1 with our work on sales rank, we will not include it here.Â  However, note that we have updated our create_query method for week 2 to include a different way of incorporating sales rank that takes advantage of OpenSearchâ€™s decay function capability.Â  Take a moment to familiarize yourself with this approach.Â  Can you improve on it?

Scenario 3: Query-Dependent Factors: Past Behavior Strongly Predicts Future Behavior in Search

Whatâ€™s better than global factors for predicting future user behavior? Actual user behavior! Humans, as a whole, like to do things other humans like to do.Â  Call it â€œgroup thinkâ€ or the hive mind or whatever, but knowing and leveraging prior interactions with your engine is one of the single most effective things you can do to improve relevance.Â  At its simplest, you can boost documents based on what documents were clicked on the most by users who previously executed the same (or similar) query.Â  At a more advanced level, you can use click models to build advanced, machine learning driven, ranking systems.Â  We will not cover the latter in this class, but we do in our Search with Machine Learning class. You can optionally do the former in level 1 below.

