Fuzzy Matching

If your results mirrored ours, when you searched for iphone4 with both â€œnameâ€ and â€œname.hyphensâ€, you got zero results.Â  One possible way of fixing this is through fuzzy matching.Â  Fuzzy matching is a built-in query mechanism for many OpenSearch query types that automatically produces alternate spellings for query terms based on edit distance.Â  So, for instance, the term â€œiPhoneâ€, when using a fuzzy matching factor, might simply become â€œphoneâ€.

Letâ€™s try this out.Â  In the Dev Console, letâ€™s modify our query a bit so that we can pass in additional parameters to the â€œmatchâ€ query, like so:

GET bbuy_products/_search
{
  "query": {
    "match": {
      "name":{
        "query": "iphone4"
      }
    }
  },
  "_source": "name"
}

Alter this query to add in a â€œfuzzinessâ€ factor of 1 and then 2.Â  Rerun the query for each case and check your results in the Project Assessment section.

Feel free to explore the other fuzziness factors on your own.Â  For instance, it's often the case that people get the first few characters of their query correct, but then mess up the spelling later.Â  What happens to your query results for â€œiphone4â€ if you set the prefix length?

Before moving on to ranking, have a look at week2/utilities/query_utils.py and observe how we incorporated these concepts into the creation of our query object.Â  If you want, you can try them out in the Flask app by commenting them out and see how they perform on queries like â€œiPhoneâ€, â€œdinseyâ€ (spelling) and various other edge case queries.

Optional: Improving RankingÂ 

As discussed earlier in the content and the project, improving ranking can be done through both query-independent means (e.g., sales rank) and query-dependent means (e.g., query-click pairs). Since we explored things like sales rank last week, this week we are going to look at how to use query logs without resorting to machine learning via a simple, but surprisingly effective statistical lookup approach.Â  In this section, weâ€™ve wired in some code to load in our clicks for you, and your job will be to leverage them to create a new query.

ğŸ‘€Note: We could also query our query index, but this is faster and easier to process since the data is static.

As a precursor, have a look at week2/__init__.py, where weâ€™ve included loading our train.csv dataset from the file system and shoving it into Flaskâ€™s application context for access at query time.Â  In this code, we build up a Pandas DataFrame (`priors`) and a GroupBy (`priors_gb`) object, which can be used to create a simple, query-dependent set of boosts by query-document pair.

Now, letâ€™s dig in and do some coding.Â  For this section, we are using Pandas.Â  You may wish to familiarize yourself with the basics before proceeding, especially the basics of grouping and iteration.

To complete this optional section, do the following:

#### W2, L1, S1: In week2/utilities/query_utils.py, implement the add_click_priors method that takes in our current query object, the user query and the GroupBy data and produces a query object that can be added to our main query object (via query_obj["query"]["function_score"]["query"]["bool"]["should"].append(click_prior_query_obj) and does the following:

Searches the id or SKU field (since they are synonymous in our case) for all IDs/SKUs that received at least one click for the given user query in the priorsgb GroupBy data.

Boost those IDs/SKUs by the total number of times that item was clicked divided by the total number of times that query was issued.

Hint: Term and Terms query are â€œsort ofâ€ what you want, but are either cumbersome (Term) or can only apply one boost for all terms (Terms).Â  What type of query allows you to pass in a string of tokens along with boosts and parses them into a query?Â 

Hint: Part of your query might look something like this (with different IDs/SKUs depending on your query): 1945674^0.026Â  1945595^0.080Â  9947181^0.011

#### W2, L1, S2: In week2/search.py, invoke your add_click_priors function to append your newly created priors query onto the main query object. (Hint: there are two places this needs to be done)

Before running the UI again (e.g., flask run), be sure PRIOR_CLICKS_LOC is pointed at train.csv.Â  If you are using Gitpod, it should do this by default when you run flask run for week2.

In your UI, do some basic testing of queries, for instance, â€œiPadâ€ and â€œlcd tvâ€. Do your results change when you add or remove the prior clicks and their weights?

Depending on how you implemented your query, you may not notice a change in results.Â  In our case, the sales rank factors far outweighed the click prior factors until we boosted our click priors on the whole.

Level 2: Implementing spell checking using term and phrase suggesters (Required)

In many cases, no amount of autocomplete, custom analyzers, fuzzy matchers or other ranking factors can overcome the fact the userâ€™s query is misspelled and yields poor results.Â  In these cases, the best thing you can do is return (hopefully) better suggestions on how the query might be improved. Or, as you often see on major search engines, you might even perform the search you think the user should have done and ask them if they really want to do their search, as in my ill-fated attempt to look for â€œprince musicianâ€:

Knowing when to do the latter (swap the userâ€™s query for a â€œbetterâ€ query) is beyond the scope of this class, but as we saw in the content, we can leverage OpenSearch to generate spelling suggestions.Â  To complete this level, implement the following:

